TaskFlow (Airflow 2.0+) uses decorators to eliminate boilerplate from DAG authoring.

Problems solved:
• No more PythonOperator wrapper boilerplate
• No more provide_context=True
• No more ti.xcom_pull() — return values ARE XComs
• No more manual dependency wiring for data passing

```python
@dag(schedule='@daily', start_date=datetime(2024,1,1))
def my_pipeline():
    @task
    def extract() -> dict:
        return {'data': [1,2,3]}  # auto-pushed as XCom

    @task
    def transform(raw: dict) -> dict:
        return {'result': [x*2 for x in raw['data']]}

    transform(extract())  # XCom + dependency automatic!

my_pipeline()
```

Dynamic Task Mapping creates one task instance per element in a list — determined at RUNTIME.

```python
@dag(schedule='@daily', ...)
def process_files():
    @task
    def get_files() -> list[str]:
        return ['a.csv', 'b.csv', 'c.csv']  # dynamic!

    @task
    def process(filename: str) -> dict:
        return {'file': filename, 'rows': 100}

    @task
    def summarize(results: list[dict]):  # receives ALL results
        print(f'{len(results)} files processed')

    files = get_files()
    results = process.expand(filename=files)  # 3 task instances!
    summarize(results)
```

.partial() fixes constant args: process.partial(bucket='my-s3').expand(filename=files)

Datasets decouple producer and consumer DAGs — consumers trigger on DATA availability, not time.

```python
from airflow import Dataset

ORDERS = Dataset('s3://bucket/orders/')

# Producer: annotates what it writes
@dag(schedule='@daily', ...)
def ingest():
    @task(outlets=[ORDERS])  # declares: this task writes ORDERS
    def load(): ...

# Consumer: triggers when ORDERS is updated
@dag(schedule=[ORDERS])  # data-driven schedule!
def report():
    @task
    def build(): ...
```

Benefits:
• If producer runs late, consumer waits automatically
• No more ExternalTaskSensor hacks
• Visual lineage in the UI
• Decouples team scheduling assumptions

Replaces BranchPythonOperator. Returns the task_id(s) of the branch to follow; other branches are skipped.

```python
@task.branch
def route(value: int) -> str:
    if value > 1000:
        return 'heavy_process'  # task_id
    return 'light_process'

@task(task_id='heavy_process')
def heavy(): ...

@task(task_id='light_process')
def light(): ...

@task(trigger_rule='none_failed_or_skipped')
def finish(): ...

branch = route(some_value)
branch >> [heavy(), light()]
[heavy(), light()] >> finish()
```

Key: downstream merge task needs trigger_rule='none_failed_or_skipped' to handle the skipped branch.

`.expand_kwargs()` allows mapping over a list of dictionaries where each dict provides different kwargs for each task instance.

```python
@task
def process_file(filename: str, delimiter: str, encoding: str) -> dict:
    ...

@task
def get_file_configs() -> list[dict]:
    return [
        {'filename': 'orders.csv', 'delimiter': ',', 'encoding': 'utf-8'},
        {'filename': 'products.tsv', 'delimiter': '\t', 'encoding': 'latin-1'},
        {'filename': 'customers.csv', 'delimiter': ',', 'encoding': 'utf-8'},
    ]

configs = get_file_configs()
results = process_file.expand_kwargs(configs)  # 3 task instances with different params
```

Vs .expand(): .expand() maps a SINGLE parameter; .expand_kwargs() maps MULTIPLE parameters simultaneously using dicts.
